Today we‚Äôre launching the FleetWorks always-on dispatcher alongside $17M in new funding led by First Round Capital as reported by TechCrunch.

In 2025, booking a single truckload can require up to 100 phone calls, emails, and text messages across freight brokers and carriers. For small trucking companies, this means over 10 hours a week of wasted time. For freight brokers, they‚Äôre trying to find a truck without being defrauded.

Our two AI agents, the always-on dispatcher and always-on carrier rep, work hand in hand to facilitate matches.

üöõ The always-on dispatcher talks to over 10,000 carriers every day over phone and text to understand what freight they‚Äôre looking for.
üíΩ The always-on carrier rep is connected with over 40 brokers to understand what freight is available and performance expectations for each carrier.
ü§ù When a perfect match is ready, the carrier is vetted for fraud, assigned to the load, and tracked end to end.

A big thank you to the thousands of brokers and carriers who‚Äôve partnered with us to change how freight moves. 

To the FleetWorks team, thank you for joining me and Quang Tran and for working tirelessly to bring our products to life.

Thank you to the amazing teams and individuals that participated in this round and backed us in the early days. We couldn‚Äôt be more excited about the launch of our always-on dispatcher and combined with $17M in new funding led by Bill Trenchard and First Round Capital.

FleetWorks started to help brokers cut down on the overwhelming noise required to book a truckload of freight. As we scaled FleetWorks, carriers wanted to know how we could help them cover their trucks.

To help carriers keep their trucks full with vetted freight, our AI-powered always-on dispatcher talks to over 10,000 carriers over phone calls and text messages to understand what freight they‚Äôre looking for. We combine this with the always-on carrier rep that‚Äôs with over 40 enterprise brokers to understand what freight is available and performance expectations for each carrier.

Thank you to all the Fleeties, customers, and investors who‚Äôve been a part of our journey! Thank you to Sean O'Kane and TechCrunch for covering our story. You can read more here: https://lnkd.in/exCR8MZa.

data.text: We've got too many hats, and we're not going to fly back with them

Half the FleetWorks team was in Chicago this week celebrating our new office in River North and deep diving with key brokerage partners. We took a little time off to cruise the river and hear about the amazing history of the city.

Great to spend time with Paul Roth, Ken S., The Anh Mai, James H., Marlon Williams, Elan Zamri, and Bailey Douglass (who was behind the camera and we've photoshopped very elegantly into this picture)

For a $1T industry, I'm always reminded of how small the freight world is. From the early Uber Freight days....so great seeing David Radom (congrats on the new role!) Eric Littel, Mike Salvo Jr. in person in Chicago. See you next time Jeff Paul, MBA!

One of my favorite things about FleetWorks is spending time with our customers to re-imagine how freight can move. Really excited to be more public about what we're doing in the coming months and we couldn't do it without brokers like Everest Transportation Systems, LLC and Simple Logistics LLC
